item.title: Ikea Hinge base
item.description:
The original Ikea element is casted in "Zamac" (light metallic material Al-Zn). Although it is a metallic element, it regularily fails and always at the same location. However, it is commonly known, that the manufacturing process imight create schrinkages at the very location of reduced sections. On top of this, this element is casted (for obvious economic reasons) and the void under the pressure zone adds fragility to it. One of the solution is to copycat the existing element AND to add a supporting section under the pressure screw. If rigidity is not sufficient, another option is to use a metallic insert right under that position too.
The proposed design is the simplest and seems working since weeks now.

item.title: Helicopter Automaton
item.description:
The purpose of this experiment was to create a functioning automaton, defined as a relatively self-operating machine. My partner Shreesh and I were inspired to construct a helicopter automaton. In our design, the helicopter launches up and down and has spinning blades attached. If you have never made an automaton before, this is the project to try out! While our design appears complex and challenging, Solidworks allows for a smooth design process and is the perfect platform for beginners.

In order to create vertical movement, a semi-circular attachment piece was inserted through the left hole at the bottom of the helicopter and capped off with an end piece. Then, this piece was placed atop an eccentric cam (attached to the handle), inside the base of the automaton. To create the spinning mechanism, another semicircular attachment piece was inserted through the helicopter, this time on the right side and with a loose fit, to ensure mobility. At the top of this piece, the blades were twisted on, while at the bottom a regular cam capped off the end. This cam was then placed at a slight angle on top of another eccentric cam. When the handle, equipped with both eccentric cams turned, the helicopter was able to move up and down steadily and the blades were able to spin. The rough dimensions of this project are 20 cm x 8 cm x 16 cm.

Design Inspiration: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yYcm3Ml2vr8

item.title: Cafflano Kompresso Dosing Funnel, Tamper and Tamping Base
item.description:
This is a set of tools for Cafflano Kompresso manual espresso coffee brewing tool.

  • 47mm Funnel for dosing
  • 56.5mm Tamper
  • Tamping base

Dosing:
Using the 47mm funnel designed for the filter basket of the Cafflano Kompresso will make it easy to dose ground coffee into the basket and also prevents coffee going outside the basket.

Tamping:
The 47mm tamper should fit to the filter basket. Not too tight, not too lose.
When tamping, if you place the filter basket on a flat surface for tamping, there will be a gap between the metal filter and the surface. So if you press the tamper too hard, the metal filter may be bent. To prevent that, I designed a tamping base that supports the metal filter from the back and that will allow you to press harder and also make the coffee flat.

All the parts can be printed as is without any support, but I highly recommend printing with brim to keep the object attached on the print bed.

item.title: Pinewood Derby Wheel Install Bench
item.description:
This is a simple tool to assist with pressing the wheels onto a pinewood derby car while ensuring that the wheel maintains an optimal distance from the car body. The slotted vertical surface has a thickness of .8mm which maintains the gap when you press the axel and wheen into the body from the outside.

Pinewood_Bench.stl is for installing wheels into drilled axel holes Pinewood_Bench_SlotGuide.stl has a raised surface for the axel slots, which helps ensure that the axel will remain high up in the slot while installing.

I'm new to 3D printing and to creating, so be easy on me! I hope someone finds this useful. Any feedback is welcomed!

item.title: Universal Spool Holder - Skateboard Wheel
item.description:
The antecedent design, with a single bearing, created an unsatisfying rotation where the spool would sometimes rub on the shaft and cause the filament to jerk. I took the same geometry for the spool interface and adapted it for use with skateboard bearings. Print this and get yourself a set of Bones Reds or similar and you'll have an incredibly smooth spool holder.

Note that this is design for 5/16" threaded rod and nuts. It might work with 8mm metric but I did not try this.

item.title: ENDER 3V2 power supply cover 92mm fan silent mod
item.description:
I modified Sectorone's PSU cover that holds a 92mm fan. I made the whole model able to fit on a 220x220 bed. I also added a recess in the model so the model WILL NOT touch the transformer inside the PSU. I also added a hole as a second way to run the fan wires, since the one on the model didnt work for me.
The cover is designed to hold a 92mm fan.
I will provide all the links to the fan and models that i used for the whole project below. My psu fan is now quieter that my parts cooler fan.
you will also need a few other models to work with this. I will also link them. Since i made the model smaller, you will need to print a second piece to cover up the exposed wires. you will understand when you remove the cover.
You will also need to print taller feet/risers for the ENER 3v2.
i also printed a 92mm fan guard.
everything except for the fan guard is required for the mod.

just use the black and yellow wire on the Noctua fan. yellow is +12v. you can just clip the pigtail off the OEM fan and the Noctua fan and solder/crimp the wires together and plug it back in. yellow to red. black to black. The fan mounts on the OUTSIDE of the PSU cover.

DO THE MOD AT YOUR OWN RISK. POWER SUPPLYS CAN BE VERY DANGEROUS. that said, it was fairy easy. no tight spaces and easy to work with.

sadly, i forgot to take pictures during the process and when i was all done.

Noctua 92x14mm fan
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B009NQM7V2/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_title_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

WhisperGod's power supply cover to cover up the exposed wires
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5146129

squirrelf's Ender 3v2 feet risers. I used the 38mm, but would probably use the 45mm if i did it again.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5146129

robertd33's 92mm fan guard. this is optional.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4727426

item.title: BMW E46 Sliding Rear Ashtray Cover Door
item.description:
Hello this is an alternative sliding cover for rear console ashtray in an e46.
Both my brothers and my e46 were missing the covers and its a bit of a pricey piece to replace for what it is.

I printed in PLA+ with layer lines running against the slats to prevent breakage.
Id recommend something like PETG but so far so good in our cars!
Included is a 10min test piece file to check fitment and flexibility of your material.

You can bend bottom of the cover gently to the curve of the slot before inserting first time to make it go in smooth. If the top of the cover with handle isnt flush when first installed you can bend it up a bit until its flat. I did what I had to do make it work with PLA+ so flexible parts between the slats are only 2 layers(.4mm) but no issues still very strong and functional.

I'd love to see some remixes with different handle designs!

enjoy : )

item.title: M3 Knurled Nut - REFERENCE ONLY
item.description:
DISCLAIMER: This model for REFERENCE ONLY.
This is a reference model for an M3 Knurled Nut w/ diameter recommendations.

I have been looking to take my hobby projects and other prints to the next level. I started to implement these knurled nuts via solder heat press into my models for my M3 screws to thread into in order to have much more secure fastening.

This model is based on these knurled nuts that I bought from Amazon:

https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07D683Q26/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_title_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I modeled these nuts as close as I can with my set of calipers based on the nut I received from Amazon.

I have included and engineering drawing of a sample assembly with an M3 screw, M3 knurled nut, and counterbored plastic with my recommended bore diameters.

I put a small 5mm diameter step in the top of the bore so that the knurled nut can be placed directly over & centered over the bore and stay there while the soldering iron tip is heating the nut to melt into the plastic.

Of course, you can play with your diameters to find what suits your project best. These measurements are just what I use.

The last picture of the full assembly is what it would look like fully pressed with a screw threaded in.
